[start section id="20103"]

Miss Mullins is a very pleasant 91-year-old who is currently hospitalized with a new diagnosis of colon cancer.  Miss Mullins was noted to have symptomatic anemia for which she was admitted and underwent a colonoscopy on December 18, 2009.  Colonoscopy showed a malignant mass in the proximal ascending/distal cecum with biopsies showing poorly-differentiated adenocarcinoma.  As part of the staging evaluation, she underwent a CT chest, abdomen, and pelvis which in addition to showing the irregular thickening of the cecum also showed a markedly dilated esophagus with some distal thickening raising the question of achalasia versus pseudoachalasia.  Miss Mullins is scheduled to undergo laparoscopic hemicolectomy with Dr. Wadsworth this upcoming Wednesday and we are being consulted for further management of the dilated esophagus that has been noted on CT-scan.
Miss Mullins notes that she feels quite well.  She denies any nausea, vomiting, or dysphagia.  She has had some problems with GERD in the past; however, this does not seem to be particularly bothersome for her.  No history of cough or aspiration pneumonias.

[end section id="20103"]

